<span id="freeTextContainer1443010582666879159">Highly philosophically enlightening and important -- if not a disturbing truth to reckon with. Ardent proposes the idea of &quot;the banality of evil&quot; in this text, recognising that &quot;normal&quot; people can do truly horrific and evil things in the modern world. <br/>Offers a detailed history of the Nazi Genocide (in part, this text reads like a history book) and, more interestingly, the circumstances of Eichmann himself. </span>
  <span id="freeText1443010582666879159" style="display:none">Highly philosophically enlightening and important -- if not a disturbing truth to reckon with. Ardent proposes the idea of "the banality of evil" in this text, recognising that "normal" people can do truly horrific and evil things in the modern world. <br />Offers a detailed history of the Nazi Genocide (in part, this text reads like a history book) and, more interestingly, the circumstances of Eichmann himself. </span>
