  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3849327988" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3849327988" />
    <a title="Oblomov" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/113963239-oblomov"><img alt="Oblomov" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640997721p2/113963239.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3849327988?book_show_action=true">Feb 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Oblomov" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Oblomov" href="/user/show/113963239-oblomov">Oblomov</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/113963239-oblomov?shelf=eat-the-rich">eat-the-rich</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3849327988" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9445972926697867099">Year of New Authors<br/><br/><b>&apos;A Biography of a Nobody: A Long, Rambling, Miserable Review of A Report on the Banality of Evil&apos;</b> by Oblomov McTwonk III<br/><br/>Amos Emil&apos;s introduction to this book is called &apos;The Excommunication of Hannah Arendt&apos;, just to give you some idea of how poorly this report was received on its first publication, with past critics believing Arendt was in some way sympathetic or defending Eichmann. Though her questioning of Israel&apos;s legal ability and motives in bringing the aged Nazi to trial</span>
  <span id="freeText9445972926697867099" style="display:none">Year of New Authors<br><br><b>'A Biography of a Nobody: A Long, Rambling, Miserable Review of A Report on the Banality of Evil'</b> by Oblomov McTwonk III<br><br>Amos Emil's introduction to this book is called 'The Excommunication of Hannah Arendt', just to give you some idea of how poorly this report was received on its first publication, with past critics believing Arendt was in some way sympathetic or defending Eichmann. Though her questioning of Israel's legal ability and motives in bringing the aged Nazi to trial would certainly have ruffled feathers, when it comes to her depiction of Eichmann himself, I don't see any kind words towards the man.<br>Arendt's Eichmann, if I can call him that, is a fool, an opportunist, a man of queasy and dithering conscience, a lacklustre figure, devoid of imagination. That anyone would consider this a sympathetic description of a man, shows how much <i>Eichmann in Jerusalem</i> was a milestone in postmodernity, putting in writing a terrible reality that many of us still struggle to believe is real even today: the banality of the Evil (disclaimer: this is my layman understanding of what that means, so I'd appreciate it if philosophy students would politely hold off with the pitchforks, but feel free to educate myself and others in the comments).<br><br>The problem with the banality of evil is that it does not mean 'anyone can be evil'. That's an incredibly easy and almost comforting thing to believe. I can say 'background of a school shooter' and you will probably have images of bullying, parental abuse, a neglected and confused child grinning manically at every team kill headshot they make in their darkened basement while screaming slurs down their headset, taking glee in the only power they have through that stimulated violence they long to be real. In a neat package you have a 'this is why it happened'. Anyone could be a school shooter <i>if</i> this was their background. Like wise, the infamous Columbine shooters are known to be bullied outsiders, obsessed with FPS games and goth music and they were part of a high school clique called the 'trench coat mafia': everything warped their minds to violence and anyone could be a school shooter <i>if</i> their childhood was so structured.<br>Except it wasn't, this is a myth. The shooters were known to be bullies, were not a member of the Trench Coats and despite how my Missus (and most others in the West) grew up on Doom, Half-Life and murdering mudcrabs to increase her dual weapon skill, she has not transformed into a serial murderer (that I'm aware of, I haven't been in the loft for a while). The shooters were not damaged in a clearly identifiable sense, and since their last act was to turn the guns on themselves, we won't ever know what led them to do what they did, and our search for a comforting 'anyone could be evil' answer of obvious influences seems fruitless. It's no wonder that in recent years, with American mass shootings ever growing, that some people have resolved their cognitive dissonance by claiming the tragedies never happened, and were all red flag operations created by sinister deep state lizards to take away their guns, i.e. <i>someone</i> evil caused it.<br>Considering all the above, it's also no surprise the reaction to Arendt's essay was as volatile and confused as it was back in the 60s.<br><br>On to the actual essay:<br>A phrase Eichmann repeatedly says when describing his descent to mass genocide is 'why not?'. Why not join the army, why not join the SS, it seemed harmless at the time, just another career choice. It put me in mind of the rather mindless Meursault in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49552.The_Stranger" title="The Stranger by Albert Camus" rel="nofollow noopener"> The Stranger</a>, another man led to murder while saying 'I could think of no reason not to' every step of the way, and Eichmann is just as drearily dull a man as Camus' protagonist in my eyes. 'Everything was incidental, a sad twist of fate' Eichmann seems to suggest in his defence.<br>Following this line of 'I didn't mean it' reasoning, Eichmann also claimed he didn't personally have anything against Jewish people. He had Jewish friends, he felt ill seeing Jewish people killed, he even saved a few childhood acquaintances, he <i>liked</i> a number of Jews:<br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1569557777ra/28207090.gif" width="300" height="200" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>To claim fondness for a group of humanity while participating in the machinations of the oppressing engine is a weird defence. It's like someone saying 'I like trans people, I have trans friends, but I'm still going to publicly claim most of them are secret perverts likely to assualt women in bathrooms, even though all statistics suggest that doesn't happen and it's trans women who are more likely to face attacks when being forced into male spaces. By the way, witches used live hedgehogs as birth control and Dumbledore was in the SAS' (Fuck off, Rowling).<br><br>The Defence's main and weak weapon throughout the trial was that Eichmann was not a monster, but merely a small cog. He had neither the power or the influence to do many of the crimes against humanity he was prosecuted for, he wanted expulsion rather than genocide as the answer to the 'Jewish question' and, most importantly, since he apparently liked Jewish people, even if he did do anything, it was because he was forced to.<br>That last point is where I think we hit the true meaning of the 'banality of evil'. It's not that 'anyone could be evil, if...' (living in Nazi Germany in this case), it's the more frightening realisation that '<i>everyone</i> can be evil without realising it'.<br>The question of what led to the Holocaust has never been answered, but the most 'comforting' one, beside the claim that most citizens were completely ignorant of what was happening, is that greedy and short sighted people (evil) signed the Treaty of Versailles, which financially and morally crippled Germany and led to the rise of the utter bastard Hitler (evil), which led to brainwashing and fear of reprisal from the SS (enforcers of evil). Bad people, basically, leading or decieving good or neutral people to ignore those riding to the gas chambers.<br>And while this would most certainly be true for many, especially younger Germans actually raised on propaganda, it still doesn't explain everything. Alas Eichmann, through his complete lack of interesting qualities as a human being but still possessing all the emotions and glands of one, shows the most horrifying piece of the puzzle:<br><br>He didn't care and just ignored it. That's it, <i>that</i> is the banality of evil.<br><br>He's not a moustache twiddling villain or an emotionally damaged mess. He's just another bureaucrat, a regular bloke, perhaps on his second marriage, has two dogs, donates to the Red Cross, once shat himself during a college/uni party and keeps catching the belt loop of his trousers on door handles. He's a normal, simple man, and he just did not care. And <i>that</i> you could extend to others of the population, e,g:<br><br>"Well, I don't think what they're doing is really nice to the Jews, I mean... Who could really? I've always tried to be nice to everyone, personally. I even promised to take care of Cohen's dog when they came for him, I'm not heartless- Yes, she had puppies, I bought the new tea pot selling a few of them. No, I've no idea where old Cohen is now. I mean I wouldn't be <i>happy</i> if I knew anything bad had happened, no one really would, but... Well look, there's more things to worry about at the minute, and what was I supposed to do? Hide him in the loft- Oh, while we're on the subject, did I tell you our Werner got promoted? Yes, he's head doctor in the camp, etc, horrifyingly mundane, etc"<br><br>Eichmann had opportunities of <i>not</i> doing many of the things he did. It was apparently easy to be reassigned and to escape the more gruesome duties without repurcussions, and yet he didn't. He didn't have to join the Nazi party, not when Hitler's manifesto of 'the Jews are the problem' was plainly open, something that should have been abhorrent to someone who supposedly liked Jewish people. He just didn't care. He could have been another dull cog, just another citizen, but 'why not join the Nazi party?'<br><br>That's what's so terrifying about the banality of evil, it's that it's so unassuming and thoughtless. Even more worrying, is that it is so mundane, you may actually be already doing it. People shrug at climate change, mutter that food banks/welfare/aid/handouts are just encouraging people to be lazy, say Rowling is just exercising free speech and if you don't like it you can ignore it, so you shouldn't criticise her and its fine for the media to give her a megaphone. Whenever we say those phrases, <i>that</i> is when the planet continues to get hotter and more species die, when austerity still ravages Britain or when Texans die in freezing tempretures because of 'small government', or when my shitty government says 'people must wait till they're 18 to even think if they want to transition', while taking away the fully reversible hormone blockers that are explicitly there so they CAN wait till they're 18 to legally make that decision, without having grown a beard or boobs in the mean time, thus screwing up there chances of passing and making their life a lot harder.<br><br>This review is already unforgivably long, to which I give my apologies and thanks if you've followed my ranting as far as you have, so now I shall pull some form of conclusion out of my rage.<br>Arendt's <i>Eichmann in Jerusalem</i> made me angry. Not at Arendt, her deadpan sarcasm and cool, objective observations of the trial was a truly engrossing read, but it made me angry that we still don't get it.<br>For a contemporary example:<br>'Donald Trump must be a narcissist with psychopathic tendencies, and his abusive Dad made him the way he was. All his supporters are dumb, racist rednecks who didn't know any better'<br>Aside from being horribly classist, misrepresenting his support base and, as usual, flippantly laying the blame on mental illness, that reasoning doesn't explain his numerous lackeys or why so many voted for the pillock. Were they all damaged bigots with mental problems? Of course they bloody weren't, they just didn't care about the bad parts, the same way my country keeps voting in the Torys despite them doing literally nothing good for Britain in any category and for any demographic, including my own majority (whatever the gammons claim) of white bloke. Edit: the Tory's <i>are</i> doing well with the vaccine roll out, one point to Slytherin, which doesn't make up the -300 for screwing up everything at the beginning of this mess and every other aspect of it now).<br>The ultimate lesson of the banality of evil is one we will not learn, and I probably haven't myself. I know climate change is real and yet I'm on a computer, typing this on components farmed from deadly mines and produced in sweat shops brought to me on fossil fuel guzzling ships, when instead I should be storming parliment and holding the PM hostage until someone actually does something to address the world's problems.<br>But what would be the point? I mean, I'm only one man and- The Thompsons got evicted? Terrible, terrible. Well, if he'd done better at school he might have had a better job than shelf stacker and could afford his rent. I mean, if he can't look after himself working over 50 hours a week, it must be because he's wasting money on something. What other reason could there be?. Rebecca? Yeah she's gone too. Yeah, I thought she was a regular woman until I was at the urinal at the Queen's Head and she was forced to use the cubicles in there instead of the ladies. Got the crap beaten out of her one time for it. Terrible, terrible, but you know how nasty some people can be. It was her own fault for leaving the house dressed like that, let's be honest. No, I think they took Rebecca to the hospital- Come on! Don't call them conversion camps, you sound like a conspiracy nut. They're <i>hospitals</i>. Anyway, yhey'll be back soon, have their head sorted out, be normal and in trousers, hopefully. I mean, I don't care how people dress personally, but come on, you're just asking for trouble if you go around- Hmm? Yeah, it is a bit hot in here. No, it's fine, weather man said the scorch wave isn't due till the thirtieth- Twentieth? <i>Shit</i>, the kids are still playing outside!'</span>
  <a data-text-id="9445972926697867099" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


