  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_632269356" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/632269356" />
    <a title="Roy Lotz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14046996-roy-lotz"><img alt="Roy Lotz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614072676p2/14046996.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/632269356?book_show_action=true">Jun 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roy Lotz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roy Lotz" href="/user/show/14046996-roy-lotz">Roy Lotz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/14046996-roy-lotz?shelf=art-of-compromise">art-of-compromise</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer632269356" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7090793976117037825">During my time in East Africa, one of the most memorable things I did was to visit the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) building in Tanzania. The Rwandan genocide was one that, I must admit, I knew almost nothing about, other than that it happened. So going into the vast research library, hearing from a lawyer who was involved in the case, and simply walking around a high-security building dedicated to prosecuting mass-murders—all this produced a great impression on me.<br/>		<br/>What wa</span>
  <span id="freeText7090793976117037825" style="display:none">During my time in East Africa, one of the most memorable things I did was to visit the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) building in Tanzania. The Rwandan genocide was one that, I must admit, I knew almost nothing about, other than that it happened. So going into the vast research library, hearing from a lawyer who was involved in the case, and simply walking around a high-security building dedicated to prosecuting mass-murders—all this produced a great impression on me.<br />		<br />What was most incredible, however, was what I learned about the origins of the genocide. The Hutu/Tutsi distinction is one that is apparently hard to pin down. Some people there even told me that the distinction was purely administrative, introduced into the country by the colonists—one that existed more on paper than in reality. It’s impossible to tell if a person is a Hutu or a Tutsi by merely looking at them. Nonetheless, this administrative distinction was enough for one million people to be slaughtered, and millions more—neighbors and acquaintances—to become murderers.<br /><br />For me, the question to ask in situations like this is precisely <i>not</i> “how horrible would it have been to be a victim?”—even though this is the question our imaginations most readily jump to. We make movies like <i>Hotel Rwanda</i> about just that very question—portraying the struggles and hardships of the victims and the heartless cruelty of the perpetrators.<br />		<br />In fact, we seem to answer this question—“how horrible would it have been to be a victim?”—in all of our literature and media about catastrophes. We watch slaves being whipped and Jews being chased, prisoners getting beaten and soldiers getting shot at. And by reminding ourselves how horrible were the sufferings of these people, we comfort ourselves with the thought that “I could never do this to a person; thank God the world is so much better now.” <br />		<br />And it is precisely this lesson that we should not draw from these calamities. Because it isn’t sociopaths that commit war crimes, carry out genocides, and enslave peoples. It’s <i>normal, average, everyday people</i>. And that’s just who we are. So, why should we think we are different?<br />		<br />In this book, Hannah Arendt makes exactly this point. Eichmann was a mindless bureaucrat, concerned only with doing his job effectively. Every psychologist that examined him proclaimed him normal, even mild-mannered. If he had been born in a different time and place, he would probably have lived out his life in complete obscurity, harming nobody. Yet he was responsible for transporting thousands of people to their deaths.<br />		<br />The reason that this could happen is not that Eichmann was stupid or evil, but because he habitually didn’t think. It was the thoughtless acceptance of the perverse moral climate of Nazi Germany that made him such an effective tool of the final solution. And it is precisely this thoughtless acceptance of authority, of the status quo, and of the values of one’s social milieu that I suspect lies at the heart of every abominable act in history. Soldiers feel righteous when they fight; masters feel justified when they mete out punishment to their slaves; Eichmann felt dutiful when he worked.<br />		<br />This kind of moral backwardness was summed up perfectly in Huckleberry Finn’s feeling of guilt when he let Jim the slave get free: “I was a trembling, because I’d got to decide, forever, betwixt two things, and I knowed it. I studied a minute, sort of holding my breath, and then says to myself: All right, then, I’ll <i>go</i> to hell.” The crime of slavery was so normal and right in Huck’s eyes that, to help a slave get free (something that we’d all regard as the right thing to do) seemed to him to be a damnable sin.<br />		<br />What’s most brilliant about this book is that Arendt arrives at this insight while hardly having to say it. It is the basic assumption that lies behind each one of her sweeping sentences and piquant remarks. It is also why Arendt takes an ironical tone that (I suspect) many will find inappropriate in a book dealing with the Holocaust. The tone is necessary, because it shows that Arendt is not on anyone's 'side', but is only trying her best to figure out what must be done in the service of justice. <br /><br />If this book was merely a damning portrait of a damnable man, it would be worthless—even harmful, in my opinion. Because the lesson is not that Eichmann is a demon that we were right to kill, but that Eichmann’s fate is a possibility for all of us if we refuse our duty to think.<br /><br /><br />[According to this <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/books/book-portrays-eichmann-as-evil-but-not-banal.html?_r=0" rel="nofollow noopener"> New York Times article</a>, Arendt was completely wrong about Eichmann's personality; apparently, he was intentionally murderous after all (and intelligent enough to critique Kant's categorical imperative). Nonetheless, I think the general message of the book—that the horrific can be made to look everyday—is still relevant.]</span>
  <a data-text-id="7090793976117037825" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

