  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2594630772" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2594630772" />
    <a title="Rossdavidh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25371127-rossdavidh"><img alt="Rossdavidh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1631399979p2/25371127.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2594630772?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rossdavidh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rossdavidh" href="/user/show/25371127-rossdavidh">Rossdavidh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/25371127-rossdavidh?shelf=black">black</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2594630772" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15967776903851566080">I was greatly impressed by Arendt&apos;s book from the very beginning, but it was not until I was finished and had a day or two to ponder it, that I realized fully the reason it was great.<br/><br/>This book grew out of a series of articles she wrote for the New Yorker magazine, concerning the trial of Adolf Eichmann in Israel. In it she coined the phrase, &quot;the banality of evil&quot;, which eventually became perhaps more well known than herself. But, while she does discuss Eichmann a reasonable amount, he is not th</span>
  <span id="freeText15967776903851566080" style="display:none">I was greatly impressed by Arendt's book from the very beginning, but it was not until I was finished and had a day or two to ponder it, that I realized fully the reason it was great.<br /><br />This book grew out of a series of articles she wrote for the New Yorker magazine, concerning the trial of Adolf Eichmann in Israel. In it she coined the phrase, "the banality of evil", which eventually became perhaps more well known than herself. But, while she does discuss Eichmann a reasonable amount, he is not the only, or perhaps even the most important, topic of the book.<br /><br />First, there is the question of what Israeli Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion's real intentions were in having Eichmann abducted from Argentina. Arendt suspects that he was trying to make a point to the Israeli people, about what they should and should not be doing in the future (fighting, not cooperating), and justice for the past was at best a side-benefit. Truth about who and what Eichmann was (or wasn't) did not figure into this, for Ben-Gurion or the prosecutor he chose for the trial (who Arendt has little but disdain for). <br /><br />Second, there is the controversial light that Arendt shone on the uncomfortable role of the leadership of Jewish communities in the organization of the Holocaust. In at least some cases, Arendt (herself a Jew who fled the Nazis) asserts that many of the organizational aspects of the Holocaust used, and in some cases even depended on, the Jewish leadership of each community. In some cases, even the literal executioners in the death camps were other Jewish prisoners. She is, however, sympathetic to the plight of those ordinary Jews who did not rise up. As she points out, they knew full well that the Nazis were capable of doing far worse than simply killing you, and if you did not cooperate, they would do it. Should you cooperate in circumstances like that? No, you should resist as best you can, even if doomed to a nasty, torturous death as a result. But one should have some sympathy for the many who simply despaired.<br /><br />Third, there is the difference in how the Holocaust happened from one country to another. There are really only two countries, Denmark and Bulgaria, where it can be said to have been resisted at least somewhat effectively by the non-Jewish population. It is another uncomfortable fact (for fans of democracy) that in both cases one of the most important causes, was the fact that the local monarch was implacably opposed. It is another uncomfortable fact that, in both cases, the local SS eventually became "unreliable" due to the local resistance, which caused them to think more about what they were being ordered to do.<br /><br />Fourth, and more closely related to Eichmann, there is the extremely uncomfortable fact that it was not a failure of conscience that caused them to follow through on their awful orders. It was more the fact that their conscience was telling them the wrong thing. In fact, Arendt asserts, it was Eichmann's conscience that kept him at his task, organizing the shipment of innocents to their death, in the last two years of the war, when even Himmler was thinking it would be a better idea to save some Jews as a bargaining chip after the inevitable Axis defeat.<br /><br />But, lastly and most centrally to the book, there is the matter of Eichmann himself. Far from being the demonic monster that one might expect, Arendt found him to be ordinary, even a bit shallow and slow. Not that he did not know what he was doing; he certainly did. But he showed repeatedly throughout the trial that he had acted, not out of sadism or any raging hatred, but rather out of ordinary careerism and bureaucratic work ethic. He was evil, but also banal. And it was the hardest thing for Israel, Europe, and all the world to come to grips with, that it was banality like his that had allowed the Holocaust to happen.<br /><br />In many ways Arendt's book foreshadows Stanley Milgram's experiments of obedience to authority, and this is no coincidence; Milgram began his experiments three months after the beginning of the Eichmann trials. Milgram's experiments shocked many people, but one gets the distinct impression from her writing that Arendt already would have been able to predict the results.<br /><br />It is a melancholy task, reading about Nazis and the Holocaust. But looming over it all is That Guy, the other Adolf, and therein lies the reason why Arendt was even greater than I had first realized. The ability that he had, most fundamentally, was not to stoke hatred or inspire obedience, but to obliterate rational thought. He retains this ability to this day, it turns out, and it works on most people. Whether they approve (fortunately, a minority nowadays) or disapprove, the other Adolf retains the ability to turn off people's ability to think rationally.<br /><br />This, by the way, is the real reason for Godwin's Law (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Godwin%27s_law">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Godwin%...</a>), and it is one which not even Godwin himself understands. Introducing The Other Adolf into the conversation, is likely to obliterate any rational discussion, because he retains this ability from the grave. He is still, nearly a century later, making people irrational, emotional, and likely to reject any appeal to reason. The most vehement anti-fascist zealot is as fully in the grip of this power as anyone. Learned scholars routinely fail to resist this super-villain's powers, even as a ghost.<br /><br />But not Arendt.<br /><br />Despite her own very personal connection to the story, Arendt's intellect is unbowed. Even more impressive, she is simultaneously empathic, able to understand how Eichmann thought. When discussing the widespread guilt that young Germans in the 1960's are said to feel, she (I think rightly) points out that their real issue is that a great many of the older Germans still running the country were obviously feeling insufficiently guilty, and the young Germans were dealing with that fact in the only way they could, by feeling guilty for them. Whether German or not, Jewish or Gentile, 1930's or 1960's, she has keen insights to share, carefully reasoned, and she relates them in well-ordered, eminently readable, sparse prose that packs more thought into a page than most other authors can in a book. She can look evil in the eye, and see that it is banal, and she will not shrink from saying so.<br /><br />We could use more like her.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15967776903851566080" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

